{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "On the pessimistic side, Bourdieu has provocatively claimed that \"public opinion does not exist\", meaning that opinion surveys lead to highly imperfect constructions of a 'popular will', affected by all sorts of measurement errors and the uneven distribution of political competence.",
    "They are not truly representative of the diversity of interests and are not an appropriate input to the political process (Bourdieu 1973).",
    "On a more optimistic note, Manin has emphasised the role played by pollsters in the expression of a public opinion (Manin 1997).",
    "He argues that the anonymous participation in a survey is some kind of 'low-cost' political expression-by comparison, to say, a public protest-and more likely to give a voice to those who are least politicised.",
    "More importantly, opinion polls lead to the decoupling between public opinion, as expressed (partially) by polls, and electoral expression as the outcome of elections."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "They are not truly representative of the diversity of interests and are not an appropriate input to the political process (Bourdieu 1973).",
    "On a more optimistic note, Manin has emphasised the role played by pollsters in the expression of a public opinion (Manin 1997)."
  ]
}